{"author":{"id":"8e1777f58c0cfe5478428be8f9fcbfe90d25e44689578335da8fc2246fe0915a"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1445090108,"nonce":"JyT22ZXDTGbtkkH7dhSQCv9a9H8=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE0ODkxNzQ1Ng==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/332#issuecomment-148917456"},"message":"\u003e I don't really know how to express this well, I'll just called it a datatype, even if that may not be a datatype in the most commonly used sense. The idea would be to have a datatype that can have a set of metadata associated to it. This metadata would include the number of samples (1 or more), the feature that is being counted (genes, exons, whatever is currently in the first column produced by count tools) and the count-data itself (per sample and feature).\n\u003e The purpose of this is that tool wrappers that produce counts would set this new datatypes as output format and assign columns and rows of their tabular output data to the correct metadata.\n\u003e Then the datatype would also take care of the conversion, so that tools that need a header-line in their input receive the correct header line, and tools that need multiple input files (one per sample) would receive this as input.\n\u003e Let me know if you think this is nonsense (honesty appreciated!). I'll be pretty busy the next weeks, but I could keep this in my inbox.\n\nThis makes sense and is technically possible already. But do you want to change code in Galaxy (the datatypes) and add new converters and other magic with every new release of such a tool? I don't the this overhead justified. The gain is minimal and only for power users, imho. What I usually do is contacting the upstream project and try to convince them to 'fix' the output format, e.g. the blockbuster output. Less work for us and everyone profits from it in a long run :)","files":null}]}